          "final_message": "The other `builtin_str` calls in `models.py` operate on numeric values (Content-Length), not on string/bytes input, so they are fine.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n**Bug:** In `requests/sessions.py` line 428, the call `builtin_str(method)` on Python 3 converts `b'GET'` to the literal string `\"b'GET'\"` instead of `\"GET\"`.\n\n**Why this happens:**\n- On Python 3, `builtin_str = str`, and `str(b'GET')` produces `\"b'GET'\"` (the `repr()` of the bytes object).\n- On Python 2, `str` and `bytes` are the same type, so `str(b'GET')` correctly gives `\"GET\"`.\n- This is triggered when a library like `python-neutronclient` passes binary strings via `safe_encode_list`, which hits the `method` parameter.\n\n**Fix applied:** Replace the unconditional `builtin_str(method)` with a decode-via-`isinstance` check, following the same pattern already used throughout the `requests` codebase (e.g., `models.py` lines 130, 342):\n\n```python\nif isinstance(method, bytes):\n    method = method.decode('utf-8')\nelse:\n    method = builtin_str(method)\n```\n\nThis is a bug in `requests` — the library should handle bytes input gracefully rather than producing a silently mangled method string that causes 404 errors.",
