          "final_message": "The fix works correctly:\n\n| Input | Old `builtin_str()` | New code |\n|---|---|---|\n| `b'GET'` | `\"b'GET'\"` ❌ | `\"GET\"` ✅ |\n| `'POST'` | `\"POST\"` ✅ | `\"POST\"` ✅ |\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n**The bug:** In `requests/sessions.py:428`, `builtin_str(method)` calls `str(b'GET')` on Python 3, which produces the literal string `\"b'GET'\"` (the repr of the bytes object) instead of decoding it to `\"GET\"`. The HTTP request then sends `\"b'GET'\"` as the method, which the server doesn't understand → 404.\n\n**Why Python 2 worked:** In Python 2, `builtin_str = str` but `str` *is* the byte-string type, so `str(b'GET')` just returns `b'GET'` (which is `'GET'`) — no problem.\n\n**The fix** (applied):\n```python\nif isinstance(method, bytes):\n    method = method.decode('utf-8')\nelse:\n    method = builtin_str(method)\n```\n\nThis checks whether `method` is `bytes` and, if so, decodes it properly to a `str` using UTF-8. Non-bytes values fall through to the original `builtin_str()` call, preserving existing behavior for strings and other types.\n\nThe real culprit is `neutronclient` calling `utils.safe_encode_list(args)` which converts the method to `bytes`, but `requests` should be resilient to receiving `bytes` for the method parameter — HTTP methods are always ASCII-safe text, so decoding is safe here.",
