          "final_message": "The fix is applied. Here's a summary of the change:\n\n**File:** `src/_pytest/compat.py:94`\n\n**Before:**\n```python\np.new in sentinels\n```\n\n**After:**\n```python\nany(p.new is s for s in sentinels)\n```\n\n**Why:** When `p.new` is a numpy array (e.g. from `@patch(target='XXXXXX', new=np.array([-5.5, 3.0]))`), Python's `in` operator evaluates `p.new == s` for each sentinel `s`. NumPy overrides `==` to return an element-wise array of booleans instead of a scalar, and when `in`'s internal `any()` tries to evaluate the truth value of that array, it raises `ValueError: The truth value of an array with more than one element is ambiguous`.\n\nThe fix uses `any(p.new is s for s in sentinels)` which performs identity comparisons (`is`) against the sentinel singleton objects (`DEFAULT`). Identity comparison always returns a single Python `bool`, regardless of what `__eq__` the object defines, so it works correctly with numpy arrays and any other type that overrides equality.",
