          "final_message": "The fix is clean. Here's what changed and why:\n\n**Problem:** On line 71 (original), `p.new in sentinels` uses Python's `in` operator. When `p.new` is a numpy array, `in` delegates to `__contains__`, which for numpy arrays returns an element-wise boolean array (e.g., `array([True, False])`) instead of a single `bool`. That array can't be used as a truth value, hence `ValueError: The truth value of an array with more than one element is ambiguous`.\n\n**Fix:** Replaced `p.new in sentinels` with `any(p.new is s for s in sentinels)`. This uses identity checks (`is`) instead of equality (`==` / `__contains__`). Since `sentinels` contains sentinel objects like `mock.DEFAULT`, identity comparison is the correct semantic — we want to know if `p.new` *is* the sentinel object, not if it's equal to it. And `any(...)` always returns a single Python `bool`, which works correctly regardless of the type of `p.new`.",
